title: For Sale:  Own your own shooting range
location: North Fort Collins, Fort Collins, Colorado
postcontent:
This posting is to test the waters to see if there would be any interest.

I have a friend who is selling his acreage north of Fort Collins. For years he has let us (his friends) shoot on his property where he has a nice shooting pit.

The property will be up for sale soon and I just hate to lose such a great place to shoot.
I can't afford to buy it myself and my wife isn't interested in moving there because it's too far from town. So I've been trying to come up a with a plan to buy the place and keep it in the family, so to speak. The final purchase price will be near $350,000 for 80 acres and a house.

One of my ideas is to form a Landowner's Consortium. We form a group of like minded folks that can buy a share or shares as part of the purchase cost. For example, a share would cost $1000. You could buy a single share, 5 shares, 10 shares or 20 shares.

As you're reading this I can hear the wheels turning. You're probably asking who has control? How do we make decisions? What about safety? What if I want out? If I have more shares do I have a bigger say?

Absolutely! All very good questions. 

Be assured that all those concerns and more would be included in a legally binding set of By Laws and Rules that we all would agree to. There would be a board of directors and democratic system for approving proposals and making decisions.

There is a nice house on this property and it would be feasible to have the house rented thereby generating income. As a consortium we would decide how best to use the funds for improving the property in the interests of the co-owners.

I've never done anything like this and there are many details that would have to be hammered out. But again, this posting is to find out how much interest there might be.

So, if owning a piece of land 20 minutes from downtown Fort Collins, where you can shoot whenever you want, is something you might be willing to put $1000 into, send me an email. If the results are overwhelming I'll take the next step and talk to a lawyer about what it would take to put this together.

My name is Michael. For now I'll retain some anonymity until this idea is cultivated to the next level. Thanks for reading and I'm exited to see what happens next.

title: For Sale:  LaRue RISR Cheek Riser
postcontent:
I have a like new LaRue RISR.  It was installed on my AR, then taken back off since I switched stocks.  It works great, especially for those using optics.  From LaRue:

Finally, a cheek riser that moves back with the charging handle when using collapsible stocks.
It's a fact that some AR's need a cheek riser to get proper cheekweld for raised scopes or rifles with raised rails. It's another fact that standard AR charging handles require a lot of travel, making it impossible to charge a rifle without moving a collapsible stock all the way to the rear. The LaRue RISR solves these problems.

Made in Texas, USA, out of glass-reinforced polymer, the RISR is spring-loaded, and travels to the rear as the charging handle is moved to the rear. When the charging handle is released, the RISR snaps forward. Designed to fit the excellent Magpul CTR butt stock without modification, the RISR only takes a few minutes to install with a phillips-head screwdriver. The RISR does not work on commercial sized furniture and only works wtih Mil-Spec stocks.

The RISR comes complete with all mounting hardware.

title: For Sale:  Bushmaster XM15-E2S (2005) M4 Type AR15 Rifle
location: Knightdale, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I'm doing some housecleaning.  This has been my primary training rifle for the past 3 years.  I don't have a round count, but I would guess it's around ~2.5K.
This rifle has also been my home defense choice.  This one was chosen for that role after taking a class (~400 rds in 1 day) and inspecting to prove it works well.  The only issue i had with this rifle is the castle nut backing out and the buffer detent popping up at around the 200 round mark (well before the 1st class).  The problem was the castle nut was not staked.  A competent armorer investigated the issue, staked the castle nut, and tested himself to ensure the issue was fixed.  After a number of classes (I try to be hard on my gear, just to ensure it'll handle abuse), I have not had that issue.
I've taken this rifle through a couple classes, and have had no issues.  Other than the one mentioned above, I had a couple type 1 failures because I didn’t properly seat the magazine.  It has been Zeroed for 50 yards, and I've been able to ring steel at 250 yards, iron sights.  Typically shoots ~2.5-3 MOA hot or cold.  Even though it is zeroed now, I will be changing the handguards back to the original bushmaster, so the POI may shift.  Please zero and confirm yourself.
I don't put too much crap on my rifle, but I did add the daniel defense lower receiver end plate with a single point sling attachment, tangoedown grip and an extended charging handle latch.  These did not make me a better shooter, but solved some problems and made manipulation easier.
This rifle begs to be shot and abused.  It’s an excellent shooter.  It’s not a tack driver, but it runs very well.  The entire bolt assembly is the original, I have not had any cracking or chipping.  Barrel and chamber are chrome lined.  I typically run either federal XM193 or wolf gold (all brass, no steel case).  It also handles federal XM855 well.  Both magpul and USGI aluminum mags work well with the rifle.  I lubricate bearing surfaces with lithium grease, and keep some CLP on hand in case she starts to bind up.
NC buyers only please, preferably concealed carry permit holders, so please have yours ready.  I reserve the right to refuse to sell the item to anyone.
Included in the sale is the rifle, with the modifications mentioned above.  No ammo nor magazines.  No trades please, cash only.  I can suggest some training facilities, and if you can prove that you’ve signed up for a class I’ll give you a discount.
My suggestions:
Add a sling and a light (preferable Surefire brand).  If you can afford it, an aimpoint is nice but not necessary.
I trust my life to this rifle (ONLY after I’ve shot ~800 rounds).  I just don’t have the need for this particular rifle anymore, so I figured someone could use it to protect their life or their family’s lives.  

Stay Sharp.
